\section{Q1}
Let $A_{\in CFG} = \{\langle G \rangle|\text{ G is a CFG that generates } \epsilon\}$. Show that $A_{\in CFG} $is decidable (computable). \newline
\indent \textbf{Sol:}
To decide $A_{\epsilon \in CFG}$,  we determine if the start symbol $S$ is nullable:
1. Initialize a set $N$ containing all variables $A$ with a rule $A \to \epsilon$.
2. Repeat until no new variables are added to $N$:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If $B \to C_1C_2...C_k$ is a rule and all $C_i \in N$, add $B$ to $N$.
    \end{itemize}
3. If $S \in N$, accept. Otherwise, reject. \newline
Since the number of variables is finite, the algorithm must halt, thus the language is decidable.

