\section{Q2}
Let $A = \{\langle R, S \rangle|R \text{ and } S \text{ are regular expressions and } L(R) \subseteq L(S)\}$. Show that A is decidable (computable). \newline
\indent \textbf{Sol:} \newline
Note that $L(R) \subseteq L(S) \iff L(R) \cap \overline{L(S)} = \emptyset$.
Convert $R$ and $S$ into DFAs $M_R$ and $M_S$.
Construct a DFA $M'$ that recognizes the language $L(M_R) \cap \overline{L(M_S)}$ using standard closure constructions for complement and intersection.
Run the decider for $E_{DFA}$ (emptiness test) on $M'$. 
If $E_{DFA}$ accepts (meaning the intersection is empty), accept. Otherwise, reject.

