\section{Q3}
 Prove that there exists a subset of $\{1\}^*$ that is undecidable (uncomputable) \newline
 \indent \textbf{Sol:}
The set of all Turing Machines is countable because each TM has a finite description, so the set of all decidable languages is also countable.
Also, the set of all subsets of $\{1\}^*$ is the power set $\mathcal{P}(\{1\}^*)$. Since $\{1\}^*$ is countably infinite, its power set is uncountably infinite.
Since there are uncountably many subsets but only countably many deciders, there must exist subsets of $\{1\}^*$ that no TM can decide.

