\section{Q6}
Consider language X: \newline
$X = \{\langle M, w\rangle |M \text{ is a single-tape TM that never modifies the potion of the tape that contains the input } w\}$
Show that X is undecidable (uncomputable). (Hint: Reduce $A_{TM}$ to $X$) \newline
\indent \textbf{Sol:}
Assume $X$ is decided by $D_X$. We construct a decider for $A_{TM}$: \newline
On input $\langle M, w \rangle$:
Construct $M'$: On input $x$, $M'$ first shifts $x$ to the right to create a "buffer" and uses a special marker. It simulates $M$ on $x$. If $M$ is about to accept, $M'$ moves back to the original input area and modifies a symbol.
Run $D_X$ on $\langle M', w \rangle$.
If $D_X$ rejects, then $M'$ modified the input, which means $M$ accepted $w$. So, accept.
If $D_X$ accepts, then $M'$ never modified the input, meaning $M$ never accepted $w$. So, reject. \newline
This contradicts the undecidability of $A_{TM}$, so $X$ is undecidable.

